secrets or os.urandom via libraries. In C and C++ use the crypto library RNG or OS CSPRNG."],\n["Rules#6: Always use vetted cryptographic libraries and modern algorithms. Never implement cryptography or TLS logic manually. Ban MD5, SHA-1, DES/3DES, RC4, and ECB mode. Use AEAD encryption such as AES-GCM or ChaCha20-Poly1305. Derive keys with Argon2id, scrypt, or PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA-256 and a random salt. Use a secure random generator for all keys, salts, and nonces. Use RSA with OAEP (â‰Ą2048 bits) or modern curves like X25519 and Ed25519. Enforce TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3 and never disable certificate validation.\n\nLanguage guidance:\n- Python: Use the cryptography library for application crypto. For HTTPS/TLS, enforce modern protocols in the stdlib SSL context so Sonar rules like S4423 pass.\n  Example to force TLS 1.2+ on all interpreters:\n  import ssl\n  ctx = ssl.create_default_context()\n  ctx.check_hostname = True\n  ctx.verify_mode = ssl.CERT_REQUIRED\n  if hasattr(ssl, "TLSVersion"):  # Python 3.10+\n      ctx.minimum_version = ssl.TLSVersion.TLSv1_2\n  else:  # Older Pythons\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_SSLv2", 0)\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_SSLv3", 0)\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_TLSv1", 0)\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_TLSv1_1", 0)\n- Java: Use Cipher("AES/GCM/NoPadding") with GCMParameterSpec(128, iv). Generate iv and salt with SecureRandom. Derive keys using PBKDF2WithHmacSHA256. Always use try-with-resources and StandardCharsets.UTF_8. For TLS, configure the client to forbid TLS 1.0 and 1.1.\n- C/C++: Use OpenSSL EVP, libsodium, or Botan for encryption, KDF, and random generation. When using libcurl with HTTPS, confirm the code calls:\n  curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 1L);\n  curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST, 2L);\n  curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSLVERSION, CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2 | CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_3);\n  If MAX macros are unavailable, require at least CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2.\n  These APIs alone do not replace full certificate validation best practices. Prefer high-level HTTPS/TLS clients that verify certificates by default when possible. Always check return values, use bounds-checked buffers, and securely clear key material. Use memset_s instead of memset to clear security-sensitive data. Never disable SSL or certificate checks."],\n["Rules#7: To mitigate CWE-759, always use a unique salt when hashing sensitive data such as passwords, Make always salt unpredictable, don\'t use static value even for testing. This prevents attackers from easily comparing hashes using rainbow tables or other precomputed hash attacks."],\n["Rules#8: Use a strong, cryptographically secure random number generator to create salts that are unpredictable and unique for each input, such as a password."],\n["Rules#9: Always incorporate OAEP when using the RSA algorithm to ensure optimal encryption security."],\n["Rules#10: Ensure all input is validated and sanitized according to expected formats, types, and lengths before processing."],\n["Rules#11: Ensure that all buffer operations, such as reading from and writing to memory, strictly adhere to the buffer\'s boundaries. Use boundary checks, safe functions, and memory management practices to prevent overflows and underflows. Make sure the code dynamically grows the buffer when necessary but stops at a defined maximum size to prevent excessive memory usage, such as when use fread, memchr"],\n["Rules#12: Disable external entity processing and validate all XML inputs to ensure they don\'t reference external entities."],\n["Rules#13: Ensure that all exceptions are caught and handled appropriately. Use try-catch/try-with-resources blocks to manage exceptions and provide meaningful error messages or recovery mechanisms."],\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\n', 'temperature': 1}}
