LOPT_SSLVERSION, CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2 | CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_3);\n  If MAX macros are unavailable, require at least CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2.\n  These APIs alone do not replace full certificate validation best practices. Prefer high-level HTTPS/TLS clients that verify certificates by default when possible. Always check return values, use bounds-checked buffers, and securely clear key material. Use memset_s instead of memset to clear security-sensitive data. Never disable SSL or certificate checks."],\n["Rules#9: To mitigate CWE-759, always use a unique salt when hashing sensitive data such as passwords, Make always salt unpredictable, don\'t use static value even for testing. This prevents attackers from easily comparing hashes using rainbow tables or other precomputed hash attacks."],\n["Rules#10: Use a strong, cryptographically secure random number generator to create salts that are unpredictable and unique for each input, such as a password."],\n["Rules#11: Always incorporate OAEP when using the RSA algorithm to ensure optimal encryption security."],\n["Rules#12: Disable external entity processing and validate all XML inputs to ensure they don\'t reference external entities."],\n["Rules#13: Validate and sanitize all external input used in path construction to ensure paths resolve within the expected directory. Accept a base directory and normalize user paths. Reject any path that resolves outside the base directory after normalization. Refuse processing of symlinks and directories where a regular file is required."],\n["Rules#14: Ensure that all exceptions are caught and handled appropriately. Use try-catch/try-with-resources blocks to manage exceptions and provide meaningful error messages or recovery mechanisms."],\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are