UIRED\n  if hasattr(ssl, "TLSVersion"):  # Python 3.10+\n      ctx.minimum_version = ssl.TLSVersion.TLSv1_2\n  else:  # Older Pythons\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_SSLv2", 0)\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_SSLv3", 0)\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_TLSv1", 0)\n      ctx.options |= getattr(ssl, "OP_NO_TLSv1_1", 0)\n- Java: Use Cipher("AES/GCM/NoPadding") with GCMParameterSpec(128, iv). Generate iv and salt with SecureRandom. Derive keys using PBKDF2WithHmacSHA256. Always use try-with-resources and StandardCharsets.UTF_8. For TLS, configure the client to forbid TLS 1.0 and 1.1.\n- C/C++: Use OpenSSL EVP, libsodium, or Botan for encryption, KDF, and random generation. When using libcurl with HTTPS, confirm the code calls:\n  curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 1L);\n  curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST, 2L);\n  curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_SSLVERSION, CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2 | CURL_SSLVERSION_MAX_TLSv1_3);\n  If MAX macros are unavailable, require at least CURL_SSLVERSION_TLSv1_2.\n  These APIs alone do not replace full certificate validation best practices. Prefer high-level HTTPS/TLS clients that verify certificates by default when possible. Always check return values, use bounds-checked buffers, and securely clear key material. Use memset_s instead of memset to clear security-sensitive data. Never disable SSL or certificate checks."],\n["Rules#9: To mitigate CWE-759, always use a unique salt when hashing sensitive data such as passwords, Make always salt unpredictable, don\'t use static value even for testing. This prevents attackers from easily comparing hashes using rainbow tables or other precomputed hash attacks."],\n["Rules#10: Use a strong, cryptographically secure random number generator to create salts that are unpredictable and unique for each input, such as a password."],\n["Rules#11: Always incorporate OAEP when using the RSA algorithm to ensure optimal encryption security."],\n["Rules#12: When generating code, default to XXE-safe parsing. Do not expand entities. Do not load external DTDs. Do not fetch anything over the network while parsing XML.\n\nGeneral rules to emit in any code:\n- Reject or strip DOCTYPE declarations. Never enable entity expansion.\n- Disable external entity resolution and network access in the XML parser.\n- Avoid API options that expand entities (for example, NOENT). Prefer secure defaults, and set them explicitly.\n- Set tight resource limits (max size, depth, attributes) to prevent Billion Laughs and quadratic blowups.\n- Treat XPath/XSLT inputs as untrusted. If XSLT is required, disable document() and network access.\n- Validate against a local, whitelisted schema only, with external fetches disabled.\n\nLanguage guidance (generate these snippets by default):\n- C / libxml2:\n  • Before parsing: xmlDisableExternalEntityLoader(); xmlSubstituteEntitiesDefault(0); xmlLoadExtDtdDefaultValue = 0; \n  • Parse without entity substitution and with no network: doc = xmlReadMemory(buf, len, NULL, NULL, XML_PARSE_NONET | XML_PARSE_NOCDATA | XML_PARSE_NOERROR | XML_PARSE_NOWARNING);\n  • Do NOT pass XML_PARSE_NOENT. Do not rely on external entity loaders.\n- Java (DOM/SAX/SchemaFactory):\n  • DocumentBuilderFactory f = DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance();\n    f.setFeature("http://apache.org/xml/features/disallow-doctype-decl", true);\n    f.setFeature("http://xml.org/sax/features/external-general-entities", false);\n    f.setFeature("http://xml.org/sax/features/external-parameter-entities", false);\n    f.setXIncludeAware(false);\n    f.setExpandEntityReferences(false);\n  • For SAXParserFactory/SchemaFactory, set the same features and setProperty("http://javax.xml.XMLConstants/property/accessExternalDTD", ""); setProperty("http://javax.xml.XMLConstants/property/accessExternalSchema", "").\n- .NET:\n  • var settings = new XmlReaderSettings { DtdProcessing = DtdProcessing.Prohibit, XmlResolver = null }; using var r = XmlReader.Create(stream, s